{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 16:42:11.372496", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis — summary and findings\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- The network fabric (hosts, DHCP server, web servers, load balancer, and FRR/OSPF routes) appears functionally connected — there is no packet loss in test pings and most RTTs are low (single-digit milliseconds).\\n- One clear anomaly was detected: the DNS server (dns_server, 10.200.0.2) exhibits very high one-way/round‑trip delays (≈1–2 seconds) to hosts, while other infrastructure hosts (dhcp_server, web servers, load_balancer, etc.) show normal low-latency behaviour.\\n- Fault localization: the problem is localized to the DNS server host itself.\\n- Likely root cause: an artificial network delay (netem qdisc) is applied on the dns_server interface (eth0), causing the ~1s latency observed to/from that host.\\n\\nDetailed observations and evidence\\n\\n1) Overall reachability\\n- The reachability sweep shows virtually all tested source/destination pairs are reachable with 0% packet loss. Example: dhcp_server -> host_1_2_2_2: 0% loss, rtt_avg ≈ 3 ms. Many host-to-host and server-to-host pings show low RTTs (typical values 1–6 ms), indicating the forwarding/routing fabric is healthy.\\n\\n2) DNS server latency anomaly (primary abnormality)\\n- From the reachability data:\\n  - dns_server -> host_1_2_2_2 (10.1.2.20): 2 packets measured give rtt_avg ~1504 ms, rtt_min ~1003 ms, rtt_max ~2004 ms (large mdev ~500 ms). Similar values for other host targets (dns_server -> host_2_4_3_2 also ~1504 ms avg).\\n  - By contrast, dhcp_server and web servers to the same hosts show RTTs in the single-digit milliseconds (e.g., dhcp_server -> host_1_2_2_2 rtt_avg ~3 ms).\\n- Direct ping from dns_server to a host produced the same effect:\\n  - dns_server -> host_1_2_2_2: rtt min/avg/max = 1003.349/1254.011/2004.889 ms (no packet loss). The pattern shows consistent ~1s baseline delay (with one packet at ~2s, others ~1s).\\n\\n3) Local config evidence on dns_server\\n- dns_server ifconfig/ip output shows eth0 configured 10.200.0.2/24.\\n- The ip_addr output for dns_server\\'s eth0 indicates the qdisc in use: \"qdisc netem state UP\" (netem is a traffic-control emulation qdisc used to introduce delay, loss, jitter, etc.). This is concrete evidence that traffic shaping/delay is applied locally on dns_server\\'s interface.\\n\\n4) Server and routing context\\n- server_access_router is 10.200.0.1 and OSPF routes are present; other servers use the same next-hop and show low latency, so routing and server_access_router connectivity appear normal.\\n- web_server_0, load_balancer, dhcp_server can ping hosts with normal low RTTs, reinforcing that the wider network is not the cause.\\n\\nFault localization\\n- Affected device: dns_server (10.200.0.2).\\n- Affected interface: eth0 on dns_server.\\n- Scope: all end-to-end traffic to/from dns_server appears delayed by ~1 second. Other servers on the same server network (10.200.0.0/24) are not similarly affected.\\n\\nProbable root cause\\n- The dns_server has a netem qdisc applied on its eth0 (as shown in ip_addr output: \"qdisc netem\"). netem commonly introduces artificial delay, packet loss, duplication, or reordering. The observed ~1–2 second consistent RTT increase matches an added delay configured via netem.\\n- There is no evidence of packet loss, routing loops, or OSPF reachability issues causing this symptom (other hosts/servers and routes are healthy), making the local qdisc configuration the most likely root cause.\\n\\nImpact\\n- DNS queries from hosts to the local DNS server will experience large latency (≈1s or more), which can cause slow name resolution and timeouts for client applications, slow web access (if clients wait on DNS), and perceived network slowness despite the underlying IP connectivity being fine.\\n- Because DNS is an infrastructure service, application performance and user experience can be significantly degraded even though other services and routing are fine.\\n\\nKey evidence (outputs)\\n- Reachability summary: dns_server -> host_1_2_2_2: rtt_avg ≈1504 ms, rtt_min ≈1003 ms, rtt_max ≈2004 ms (no packet loss).\\n- Direct ping from dns_server: rtt min/avg/max = 1003.349/1254.011/2004.889 ms, pipe 2 (4/4 packets received).\\n- dns_server ip_addr/ifconfig: eth0 present as 10.200.0.2/24 and ip_addr lists \"qdisc netem state UP\" for eth0 — indicating netem is active on that interface.\\n- Other servers (dhcp_server, web_server_0, load_balancer) show normal qdiscs (fq_codel) and low RTTs to hosts, confirming the issue is limited to dns_server.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- The network fabric and OSPF routing appear healthy and hosts reach servers without packet loss.\\n- The DNS server (dns_server) is the single localized point exhibiting abnormally high latency to the host subnets.\\n- The most likely root cause is a netem traffic-control configuration on dns_server\\'s eth0 introducing an intentional or accidental ~1 second delay. This will materially impact DNS responsiveness and client behavior despite otherwise normal connectivity.\\n\\nIf you want, I can:\\n- show the exact ip/tc qdisc state on dns_server (tc qdisc show dev eth0) and any tc rules, and\\n- re-run targeted pings/traces from other servers to quantify the delay further.\\n(I have not performed any remediation steps — only diagnostic data collection and analysis.), please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='1def66f9-1183-4d13-b6a1-15d7919fbc78'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
